 of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Langley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called Langley or <i>Longley</i> (in Kent, Sussex, Hertfordshire, Norfolk, Somerset, Shrops, Lancashire, Durham, and many other counties), themselves from Old English <i>lang</i> ‘long’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, glade, clearing’.","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Langlif</i> (Old Norse <i>Langlíf</i> ‘long’ + ‘life’ or ‘body’).","Americanized form of French   Langlais  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Langlais","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Pierre, Emile, Marcel, Normand, Albertine, Armand, Cecile, Enoil, Herve, Jacques, Laurent.","French: ethnic name for an Englishman, from <i>Anglais</i> ‘Englishman’, with fused definite article <i>l'</i>. Compare   Langley  .","History: Daniel Sargent <i>dit</i> Sérien and Langlais from Worcester, MA married Marguerite Lavoie in Rivière-Ouelle, QC, in 1718. Joseph Weber <i>dit</i> Langlais from Boston, MA married Marie-Charlotte Guillet in Cap Saint-Ignace, QC, in 1725."]},{"name":"Longley","meanings":["English (mainly Nottinghamshire and South Yorkshire): variant of   Langley  . Compare   Longpre   2."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":25,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William de Langley was born in 1234, in Shipton-under-Wychwood, Oxfordshire, England as the son of Henry de Langley. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1260, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1234–1260":"1234–1260","1258–1286":"1258–1286","1210–1240":"1210–1240","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1234":"1234","1210":"1210","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","Langley Manor Shipton under Wychwood, Oxfordshire, England":"Shipton-under-Wychwood, Oxfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1234–1260":"1234–1260","1258–1286":"1258–1286","1210–1240":"1210–1240","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1234":"1234","1210":"1210","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1260":"1260","Langley Manor Shipton under Wychwood, Oxfordshire, England":"Shipton-under-Wychwood, Oxfordshire, England"},"fr":{"1234–1260":"1234–1260","1258–1286":"1258–1286","1210–1240":"1210–1240","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1234":"1234","1210":"1210","1286":"1286"